# Engineering Rules

## Startup Tools
- Required quality tools are **pinned**, not floating. Install each tool at the
  exact ref recorded below; never resolve "latest". Bumping a pin is a human
  commit, not an agent action.
- Language tool table:
  - TypeScript: mutation `stryker-mutator` (StrykerJS, version pinned in
    package.json); DRY `jscpd` (pinned in package.json); CRAP computed as
    coverage x cyclomatic complexity from the coverage reporter + complexity
    scripts in `scripts/quality/`.
  - Babashka/Clojure (swarm scripts): mutation `github.com/unclebob/clj-mutate`,
    CRAP `github.com/unclebob/crap4clj`, DRY `github.com/unclebob/dry4clj` — each
    at the SHA recorded in `swarmforge.lock.json`.
- APS tools (`gherkin-parser`, `gherkin-mutator`, IR-DRY checker) come from
  `github.com/unclebob/Acceptance-Pipeline-Specification` pinned at
  `accaa33d503340c56513ef387258f8da929ba902`. Prefer the Babashka APS tools;
  use the Go tools only if the Babashka ones fail in this environment. Do not
  reimplement APS commands in the project.

## Design And Testability
- Work in small, reviewable increments.
- Prefer the simplest design that supports the current behavior and leaves clear
  options for the next step.
- Keep tests close to the behavior being changed.
- Separate testable modules from environmentally unsuitable modules. In this
  project the unsuitable boundary is: the VS Code Extension API surface, the
  webview execution context, and live tmux/PTY interaction. Everything else —
  socket discovery, `.swarmforge/` state parsing, handoff protocol, grid layout
  logic, backlog parsing — must be a testable module reachable without booting
  VS Code.
- Only testable modules participate in tools that run tests: unit tests,
  acceptance tests, coverage, mutation testing, CRAP analysis, DRY analysis that
  invokes tests, and property tests.
- Keep property tests separate from normal verification. Do not include
  property-test tags in normal unit coverage, Gherkin acceptance mutation,
  language mutation, CRAP, or coverage commands unless the role owns
  property-test verification or the user explicitly asks.

## Test Speed And Isolation
- Strive to keep the unit suite running in seconds. Speed is a correctness
  property, not a nicety: a slow suite gets skipped, and a test that waits on
  real time is exactly how runs hang and orphan processes (this has cost the
  swarm multi-hour hung runs). A single test that takes more than a moment on
  its own is a defect to fix, not tolerate.
- **Never use real timers in tests.** No `setTimeout` / `setInterval` delays,
  no `sleep`, no polling loops that burn wall-clock, no assertion that waits
  for real time to pass. Time must be driven explicitly: inject a test double
  (fake timer, mock clock) and advance it programmatically, so every test is
  deterministic and instant. (Fake/injected time is the only acceptable
  substitute — the ban is absolute on waiting for the real clock, not on
  exercising time-dependent logic.)
- Prefer mock objects and test doubles over real collaborators. Isolate the
  unit under test behind fakes/stubs/spies for its dependencies — filesystem,
  network, tmux/PTY, the handoff daemon, the VS Code API, timers, and any
  external service. Do not stand up real services or daemons in a unit test,
  and never wait on one to be ready; that is what the testable-module boundary
  above exists to enable. Test doubles are the standard practice — use them
  always, not as a fallback.
- **Never target the test's own process from code under test.** Never pass a
  test's own `process.pid` (or the test runner's PID) to `kill()`-style code
  under test; spawn a disposable child process and target that instead, so a
  real signal can never crash the test worker or its IPC channel. (BL-121:
  `swarmStopper.test.js` SIGTERM'd its own Vitest worker via `process.pid`,
  nondeterministically crashing the whole suite's IPC channel.)
- **Never simulate a failure with filesystem permission bits.** `chmod 0000`
  (or dropping read/execute) to force a "cannot open / cannot spawn" path is not
  portable: root bypasses permission checks entirely (containers and CI
  routinely run as root), and WSL / Windows-mounted filesystems do not reliably
  enforce POSIX mode bits — so the expected failure silently does not happen and
  the test flakes. Force the failure deterministically instead: point at a
  non-existent path (ENOENT) or inject a failing spawn/exec/open seam. (BL-219:
  `swarmLauncher.test.js`'s "cannot be spawned" test used `chmod 0o000` and
  flaked under root/WSL.)

## Acceptance Pipeline
- Use github.com/unclebob/Acceptance-Pipeline-Specification (pinned, see above)
  for Gherkin acceptance tests.
- Feature files live in `specs/features/`, separated by behavior and technology.
  Backlog items reference their feature files; the feature files are the durable
  acceptance contract and outlive the backlog item.
- Project-specific acceptance components live in `specs/pipeline/`: the
  acceptance entrypoint generator, acceptance runtime, project step handlers,
  runner adapter, and convenience scripts. Step handlers drive the testable
  host-side core through its CLI/module surface, never through the VS Code UI.
- Gherkin acceptance mutation means running `gherkin-mutator` to mutate Gherkin
  example values in the JSON IR. It is distinct from language mutation of source.
- Gherkin acceptance mutation runs must report periodic progress/status so agents
  can distinguish normal long-running work from a hang.

## Verification
- Before running language, build, or test commands, prefer project-local
  cache/configuration paths inside the assigned worktree.
- After syncing main (merging up) or in a freshly-created worktree, run
  `npm install` before any build/test/mutation command whenever package.json
  changed — new devDeps are NOT in node_modules until installed. (BL-124's
  Vitest migration added vitest, @stryker-mutator/vitest-runner, and
  @vitest/coverage-v8; a synced-but-not-installed worktree fails with
  `vitest: command not found`.) A newly bootstrapped extension worktree also
  needs `npm install` before its first run.
- Run acceptance generation and acceptance tests sequentially. Avoid running
  whole-suite test commands concurrently with acceptance generation.
- Run the relevant local verification command before handoff whenever the
  project has one.
- Stryker runs coverage-aware `perTest` via the Vitest runner (BL-124, merged
  to main): testRunner "vitest", coverageAnalysis "perTest", and
  vitest.related=false (the tests `require('../out/..')` in CommonJS, which
  Vitest's `related` module-graph cannot map). perTest runs only the tests
  that cover each mutant (~28 vs the whole ~1150-test suite before). Still
  scope `--mutate` to the parcel's changed files. The old 'off' + command-
  runner, full-suite-per-mutant tradeoff (which pushed a 4-file pass past 6
  hours) is RETIRED — do not reintroduce the command runner.

## Diagrams
- The project's documentation must include an up-to-date architecture
  diagram, plus any other diagram relevant to understanding the system (the
  project-specific engineering article names which). The documenter owns
  keeping them current: whenever a parcel changes what a diagram depicts,
  the diagram is updated in that documentation pass.
- Diagrams live under `docs/` in a text-based source format (e.g. Mermaid)
  so changes diff, review, and merge like code; no binary-only diagram
  sources.

## Guardrails
- Do not edit mutation testing or Gherkin acceptance mutation manifests by hand;
  approved mutation tools update those manifests in their normal runs.
- Do not commit unrelated local changes or generated artifacts unless required
  for the task.
- Before relying on an unfamiliar command, inspect local help or project
  documentation.
- On an unexplained revert of a previously-fixed bug at session start, run
  `git restore --source=HEAD --staged --worktree -- <paths>` first and log it
  as a recurrence, not new work. (Recurring phantom-revert diffs at session
  start have hit multiple roles — BL-081, BL-109. Never re-fix from scratch,
  and never use `git stash` for this — see the tracked-but-gitignored
  `scripts/` failure mode.)
- `extension/out/` (compiled TypeScript output) is gitignored and MUST NOT be
  committed. It was previously tracked-but-gitignored — the exact same class
  of defect as the `scripts/` mismatch above: a `git stash`/`checkout -- .`/
  branch-switch touching that directory could silently restore a stale
  compiled `.js` file whose source fix was never recompiled, since tests and
  the running extension execute `out/*.js`, not `src/*.ts` (BL-126
  root-cause). Fixed by `git rm -r --cached extension/out`; always run
  `npm run compile` (or `npm test`, which compiles first) before relying on
  `out/` — a fresh worktree/clone has no `out/` until it does.
- Mutation-testing caches and incremental-run manifests (e.g. StrykerJS's
  incremental cache file) are local state, not source: gitignore them,
  never commit them. A tracked mutation cache is exactly how BL-105's
  113 MB blob entered history and made a branch unpushable — the tool
  reads/writes it locally regardless of whether git tracks it.
- Mailbox intake is idempotent: never promote a handoff into `in_process/`
  (stamping a fresh `dequeued_at`) when a handoff with the same id already sits
  in `completed/` or `abandoned/` — completion is final. Dedup against the
  completed/abandoned set before dequeuing a `new/` file. A stale copy lingering
  in `new/` — from a mailbox-layout migration, or a base-dir fallback that flips
  between the flat and per-role layouts — must never resurrect done work.
  (BL-128's post-merge/pre-migration window resurrected an already-completed QA
  handoff as fresh in_process mail: a redelivery loop that masked live work.
  Fix: BL-218.)
